  <!-- FORMBY PROPERTY SECTION, UNIQUE -->
  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f1f5f9;">
    <div class="container">
      <span class="pf-section-label">FORMBY PROPERTY KNOWLEDGE</span>
      <h2 style="text-align:center;">Formby's Larger Homes Need a Designed Heating System. Not an Off-the-Shelf Combi Swap.</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">Most Formby properties are 3 to 5 bedroom detached or semi-detached homes. Many are being renovated, extended or upgraded. These properties need a heating system that is designed for their specific layout, not a standard installation that works for an average 3-bed semi.</p>

      <div style="display:grid;grid-template-columns:1fr;gap:1.5rem;margin-top:2rem;">

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Multi-Zone Heating for Larger Formby Homes</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">A 4 or 5-bed Formby property heated by a single-zone system has one thermostat and one temperature for the entire house. This wastes energy by heating unused rooms to full temperature and makes it impossible to keep a home office warmer than a spare bedroom. A multi-zone system divides the house into separate heating circuits, typically upstairs and downstairs, with independent thermostats for each zone. This gives independent control, reduces gas consumption in larger homes by 15 to 25% compared to a single-zone setup, and is the correct system design for a property of this size. We design zone systems at the free survey for every Formby property with 10 or more radiators, at no additional survey charge.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Underfloor Heating Circuits in Kitchen Extensions and Renovation Areas</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">Formby homeowners extending or renovating frequently want underfloor heating in the new kitchen, utility room or open plan ground floor extension rather than radiators that break up the wall space. Wet underfloor heating circuits connected to the system boiler are the right solution for these spaces. We design and install these circuits alongside the main radiator system as a single installation. The underfloor circuit connects to the system boiler via a dedicated zone and its own thermostat, giving independent control over the extension's floor temperature while keeping the rest of the radiator system on its own zone. This design approach is common in our Freshfield and Formby Village installations where kitchen extensions are frequently part of broader renovation projects.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card" style="border-top:4px solid var(--navy);">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">System Boilers and Unvented Cylinders for Multi-Bathroom Formby Homes</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0 0 0.75rem;line-height:1.65;">A Formby home with 3 bathrooms and a combi boiler will struggle to deliver satisfactory hot water flow when more than one bathroom is in use simultaneously. The correct solution for multi-bathroom Formby properties is a system boiler paired with an unvented mains pressure cylinder. This delivers full mains pressure hot water to every outlet in the house simultaneously, with no competition between bathrooms. Our G3 qualified engineers design and install these systems regularly across L37. The free survey for a multi-bathroom Formby property includes cylinder sizing, boiler sizing and zone design alongside the full radiator layout.</p>
          <div style="background:#eff6ff;border:1px solid #bfdbfe;border-radius:var(--radius-sm);padding:0.75rem 1rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.88rem;color:#1e40af;margin:0;font-weight:600;">Our engineers hold G3 qualification for unvented cylinder installation and annual inspection. This is a legal requirement for this work. We are one of few companies in the Formby area that can design, install and certify the complete system in a single project.</p>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="pf-card pf-card-left-orange">
          <strong style="display:block;color:var(--navy);font-size:1rem;margin-bottom:0.35rem;">Smart Multi-Zone Controls for Formby Renovations</strong>
          <p style="font-size:0.93rem;color:var(--muted);margin:0;line-height:1.65;">A multi-zone Formby heating system deserves multi-zone smart controls. We install Nest and Hive systems that give independent zone control from a phone app, allowing you to set different schedules for upstairs and downstairs heating, turn on the underfloor circuit in the kitchen extension from the sofa, and monitor energy use by zone. For larger Formby properties where heating runs longer and costs more, smart controls typically deliver an annual saving of £150 to £300 compared to a standard single-zone programmer. We set up the controls and walk you through the app before we leave.</p>
        </div>

      </div>
    </div>
  </section>


  <!-- SIGNS -->
  <section class="pf-section" style="background:#f8fafc;">
    <div class="container">
      <h2 style="text-align:center;">Signs Your Formby Home Needs a Central Heating Upgrade</h2>
      <p class="pf-sub">These are the most common situations reported by Formby homeowners before calling us for a free survey.</p>
      <div class="pf-signs" style="margin-top:2rem;">
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Single-zone heating in a large Formby home</strong><p>If your 4 or 5-bed property runs on a single thermostat, you are heating unused rooms to the same temperature as living spaces and paying for it. A multi-zone upgrade resolves this and typically reduces heating bills by 15 to 25%.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Kitchen extension with no underfloor heating</strong><p>A newly extended ground floor without underfloor heating is a missed opportunity. If you are planning an extension or renovation, this is the time to include wet underfloor circuits connected to your system boiler. Retrofitting later is significantly more disruptive and more expensive.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Hot water pressure poor in upstairs bathrooms</strong><p>Poor pressure in an upstairs bathroom of a large Formby property almost always indicates the wrong system type for the property. A system boiler with an unvented cylinder delivers full mains pressure to every bathroom simultaneously. We test mains pressure and assess the correct system at the free survey.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Heating bills disproportionately high for property size</strong><p>A large Formby home on a single-zone system heats every room to the same temperature all the time. Multi-zone control with smart thermostats resolves this. A properly designed system with zone control and smart controls in a large property typically reduces bills by 20 to 35%.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>Rooms always cold despite the heating being on</strong><p>Missing radiators, an undersized boiler or a poorly balanced system means the heating can never keep up. A free survey identifies whether a radiator addition, system balance or full upgrade is the right solution for your Formby property.</p></div></div>
        <div class="pf-sign"><div><strong>EPC rating of D, E, F or G</strong><p>A poor EPC rating on a Formby property, particularly relevant for buyers and sellers where documentation is increasingly requested before exchange, is almost always linked to an inefficient heating system. A new system with smart controls is the single most impactful EPC improvement available.</p></div></div>
      </div>
